	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>France wants to increase its Indian Ocean tuna capacity by 500%</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>France’s Fleet Development Plan (FDP) submitted to the Indian Ocean Tuna Commission (IOTC) shows that the country intends to increase its tuna-fishing capacity from 4,638 GT (gross tonnage) to 23,430 GT in the Indian Ocean by 2015. France intends to add one new purse-seiner each year, from 2009 to 2012, and 15 small tuna vessels in 2015. In addition, the country has indicated that seven existing long-liners, currently configured to target toothfish, will be converted to fishing for tuna in the future. No specific time-table for the introduction of these vessels has been provided. Nevertheless, this will contribute to an increase in capacity of 8,230 GT. Apart from France, only Malaysia and Mauritius have submitted FDPs to the IOTC. Malaysia wants to increase its fleet to 112 vessels by 2012, and Mauritius intends to increase its fleet to 20 vessels with capacity varying from 200 to 800 GT each by 2015. </p><p>Later on in August, the director of the French tuna-boat owners association for purse-seiners, Orthongel clarified France’s willingness to fish ‘better’ and not ‘more’, highlighting that several new purse-seiners of the French fleet, although larger than the others (with greater GT), are not going to fish a greater tonnage of tuna than the others because these boats have deep-freezing units (which occupies some of the GT) in order to produce higher-value fish. The owners of French tuna purse-seiners do not intend to produce more but to produce ‘better’ (no tuna under 1.5 kg, better quality products). </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Press article and interviews, <i>ATUNA</i>, 23 June 2010 and August 11 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.atuna.com/" target="_self">http://www.atuna.com/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The clarification by the French purse-seiner sub-sector is welcome, but it remains to be seen whether, after taking into account the impact of piracy (which led to a decrease in overall fishing capacity in the Indian Ocean), the proposed increase in French fishing capacity– consistent with the global Fishing Development Plan of the IOTC - will not still lead to overexploitation of resources. More generally, this underlines the importance for urgent action by coastal states themselves to propose a clear plan for the sustainable development of their fleets, so that their rights can be recognised and taken into account.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
